          "distinct": false,
          "id": "f478912382bd3fc1fcd44dfd19659ac271e228fa",
          "message": "docs: Propose datapoint-level enum attributes for metrics (#3369)\n\n# Change Summary\n\n## Datapoint-level enum attributes for metrics\n\nDesign-only RFC (doc:\n`rust/otap-dataflow/docs/telemetry/datapoint-enum-attributes.md`).\nTracking issue: #3300.\n\n### What changed from the previous drafts\n\nThe prior draft standardized two interoperable export shapes (name-split\n\"granular\" and attribute-split \"agnostic\") and let operators pick. Per\nreview feedback this revision drops the dual-shape approach and,\nfollowing further discussion, also drops the earlier\n┬ĀSignalCounter┬Ā/┬Āsignal_metric┬Ā instrument idea:\n\n1. One format. Signal becomes a datapoint attribute\n(`signal`=`logs/metrics/traces`), matching the\nCollector's┬Ā`otelcol.signal`.\n2. Generalize. `signal` is one instance of bounded enum attributes that\nvary per datapoint (e.g. ┬Ā`outcome`=`success/error`,\n┬Āhttp.response.status_code), each with a static/dynamic qualifier.\n3. Keep using `metric_set`/`attribute_set` concepts. This is not a new\ninstrument family. Enum attributes are extra dimensions on a set's\ndatapoints, not separate sets or instruments. Sets with no enum\nattributes keep today's behavior and hot path.\n\n### Enum attributes: static vs dynamic\n\nAttributes are grouped into reusable `#[attribute_set]` structs and\nreferenced by a `metric_set`:\n\n- **Static** (`static_attributes = <Set>`) ŌĆö value fixed at\nregistration; no per-call argument (e.g. `journald`, a logs-only\nreceiver, binds `signal = logs` once).\n- **Dynamic** (`dynamic_attributes = <Set>`) ŌĆö value supplied per\nrecord. `durable_buffer_processor` folds its 8 hand-rolled loss counters\ninto a single `lost_items` metric via `signal` + `outcome`.\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, AttributeEnum)]\npub enum Signal { Logs, Metrics, Traces }\n#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, AttributeEnum)]\npub enum LossOutcome { Dropped, Expired }\n\n#[attribute_set(name = \"durable_buffer.loss.attrs\", dynamic)]\npub struct DurableBufferLossAttributes {\n    #[attribute(key = \"signal\")]  pub signal: Signal,\n    #[attribute(key = \"outcome\")] pub outcome: LossOutcome,\n}\n\n#[metric_set(name = \"otap.processor.durable_buffer.loss\",\n             dynamic_attributes = DurableBufferLossAttributes)]\npub struct DurableBufferLossMetrics {\n    #[metric(unit = \"{item}\")] pub lost_items: Counter<u64>,\n}\n```\n\nBecause every attribute is a closed enum, worst-case cardinality is\nknown at compile time (the product of variant counts), so codegen can\nwarn before a set exceeds the SDK's runtime cardinality limit - a\nguarantee free-form string attributes can't offer.\n\n### Recording API\n\nThe recorder supplies dynamic variants through a single struct-bound\nview, `with(...)`, which returns a bound view of the whole set:\n\n```rust\nloss.with(DurableBufferLossAttributes { signal: Signal::Logs, outcome: LossOutcome::Expired })\n    .lost_items\n    .add(120);\n```\n\n### Scope\n\nDesign only - no instrumentation is migrated in this PR. Goals,\nbackground, worked examples (`durable_buffer_processor`, `journald`),\nand open questions are in the doc.\n\n## What issue does this PR close?\n\n* Related to #3300 \n\n## How are these changes tested?\n\nN/A\n\n## Are there any user-facing changes?\n\nN/A\n\n### Changelog\n\n<!--\nUser-facing changes need a .chloggen/*.yaml entry. Copy the\nTEMPLATE.yaml\nin go/.chloggen/ or rust/otap-dataflow/.chloggen/ and fill in the\nfields.\nIf not required, include `chore` in the PR title.\n-->\n\n* [x] Added a `.chloggen/*.yaml` entry, OR this PR is a `chore`\n(indicated in title).\n\n---------\n\nCo-authored-by: Copilot Autofix powered by AI <175728472+Copilot@users.noreply.github.com>",
